    "id": "UgxrH_IKPMBiQODO4Md4AaABAg",
    "author": "@davidvwilliamson",
    "author_channel_id": "UChZalwv3NkNtfU9paagHQ4g",
    "text": "won't a friction drive creep unpredictably. unlike cogwheels. so is it suitable for a 3d printer mechanism? won't it cause inconsistent movement?",
    "likes": 2,
    "published_at": "2025-07-23T18:40:20Z",
    "reply_count": 2,
    "replies": [
      {
        "id": "UgxrH_IKPMBiQODO4Md4AaABAg.AKvzsN79StuAKw1NloHRTu",
        "author": "@ThinkingandTinkering",
        "author_channel_id": "UC4AkVj-qnJxNtKuz3rkq16A",
        "text": "Oh yeah - but pointing out a potential problem is only half the issue mate - how would you solve it?",
        "likes": 2,
        "published_at": "2025-07-23T19:02:15Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "UgxrH_IKPMBiQODO4Md4AaABAg.AKvzsN79StuAKwCbaM2sVm",
        "author": "@angelusmendez5084",
        "author_channel_id": "UC3Tl-lMNqw87ZYe-PJr2YtA",
        "text": "- Minimize torque spikes by reducing acceleration\n- Limiting friction drive to low-load axes\n- Using thermally stable filaments for the pieces\n- Using higher-friction balls\n- Adding rotary encoders to the motors ( to detect movement slippage)?",
        "likes": 1,
        "published_at": "2025-07-23T20:40:23Z"
      }
    ]
  },
